The '''geology of [[Monaco]]''' is closely related to the end of the Western Alps, forming the small country's steep [[cornice]] coastline. During the last 2.5 million years of the [[Quaternary]] high sea levels between glaciations formed erosion terraces and left behind coastal sediment deposits. Beach sands and mixed with frost chippings and other cold-weather remnants of the glacial period and preserve large mammal remains and archaeological remains of early humans in the Gîte des Moulins Cave and the Jardin Exotique. Monaco hosts the International Hydrographic Bureau. <ref>{{cite book |author=Moores, E.M.; Fairbridge, Rhodes W.|year=1997|title=Encyclopedia of European & Asian Regional Geology|publisher=Springer|p=540}}</ref >

